# Viral Bionic Anomaly
This floor is haunted by a phantom of the past. You encounter a presentation created by the last employee of a forgotten corporation, made just minutes before the Citadel awoke.

Rumor has it that the corporation predicted the rise of the Citadel. Within the slides, a "starter pack" holds the clues you need. Use it to confront the "final boss," a threat trapped inside a macro hidden deep within the presentation, and claim the key to the next floor.

## My solve
**Flag:** `citadel{gr4b_y0ur_l4bubus_m4tch4s_4nd_dub41_ch0c0l4t3s_y0u_4r3_1n_f0r_4_r1d3}`

Sub RunPayload()
    Cw9 = ZqL9D8()
    Fx8 = JvQ1g()
    Ly7 = Yu89()
    
    flag = Cw9 & Fx8 & Ly7

    End Sub

In the VBA script we can see 3 main functions - ZqL9D8, JvQ1g and Yu89. They are called in RunPayload and their output is concatenated to form flag.

Function ZqL9D8 has 21 different encrypted strings, they are concatenated and Base32 decoded as seen from the logic and character set provided in the function.

Similiarly, function JvQ1g has 26 different encrypted strings, they are concatenated and Base16 decoded as seen from the logic and character set provided in the function.

Similiary again, function Yu89 has 18 different encrypted strings, they are concatenated and Base64 decoded as seen from the logic and character set provided in the function.

Now that we know the logic behind the flag encryption, we can reverse it to get flag.

After initial decryption of the flag we can see that flag starts with FF D8 FF E0 which is JFIF in ascii and also the magic bytes of a JPG file. so we need to save the decrypted flag as a JPG file.

Here is the solve script :

## What I learned
From this challenge, I learned how VBA macros can be used to hide or obfuscate data inside Microsoft Office files like .pptm. 
By extracting and analyzing the macro, I understood how the Base32 encoding scheme works and how to reverse it to retrieve hidden information. 
I also learned how to read and interpret VBA functions, identify encoded payloads split across multiple variables, and reconstruct them into a single string for decoding. 
This exercise improved my understanding of file-based malware and steganographic techniques often seen in CTFs and real-world document exploits. 
Most importantly, it strengthened my ability to reverse-engineer code logic, convert it into equivalent Python scripts, and automate the decoding process to uncover the final flag.
